# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1859-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The **1859 Virginia gubernatorial election** was held on May 26, 1859, to elect the governor of Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1859-virginia-gubernatorial-election] In February 1859, Archibald Campbell and John Curtiss Underwood proposed a coalition between the Republican Party of Virginia and Whig Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1859-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, the Whigs refused to change their position on slavery.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1859-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Republicans did not run a gubernatorial candidate and the party told its members to abstain from the election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A United States presidential election was held on November 6, 1860.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party ticket of Abraham Lincoln and Hannibal Hamlin emerged victorious.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1860, the United States was divided over the issue of slavery, and four major political parties had nominated candidates in the 1860 presidential election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president James Buchanan, a Democrat, did not seek re-election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The anti-slavery Republican Party nominated Abraham Lincoln, who previously had been a one-term Whig Representative from Illinois, for president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Its platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states where it existed, but opposed its extension into the territories.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party, which sought to avoid disunion by resolving divisions over slavery with some new compromise.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Constitutional Union Convention put forward former Tennessee Senator John Bell for president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the 1860 Democratic National Convention adjourned without agreeing on a nominee, a second convention nominated Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas as the Northern Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas's support for the concept of popular sovereignty, which called for each territory's settlers to decide the status of slavery within the territory, alienated many radical pro-slavery Southern Democrats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With President Buchanan's support, Southern Democrats held their own convention, nominating Vice President John C.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a majority in the Electoral College, with all his Electoral College votes coming from Northern states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He prevailed in 18 states, won 180 electoral votes, and received 39.7 percent of the popular vote.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas won the second-highest popular vote total, but won only the state of Missouri; he was the only candidate in the 1860 election to win electoral votes in both free and slave states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge won 11 states, finishing third in the popular vote, while Bell finished fourth in the popular vote and won the electoral votes of the states of Kentucky, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the last presidential election in which it appointed its presidential electors at the discretion of the state legislature rather than by popular vote (and was the only state to do so), the presidential electors of South Carolina cast their ballots for Breckinridge.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 election was the first of six consecutive Republican presidential victories.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's election as the first Republican president served as the main catalyst for Southern secession and the American Civil War.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His election motivated seven Southern states, all of which had voted for Breckinridge, to secede from the United States before Lincoln's inauguration on March 4, 1861.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Civil War began less than two months after the inauguration with the Battle of Fort Sumter, after which four more slave states seceded.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 presidential election conventions were unusually tumultuous, particularly because a split in the Democratic Party had led to both Northern and Southern party conventions.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860 after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed by Salmon P.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois was less well-known and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, and was an able politician with a Whig background.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase's firm anti-slavery stance made him popular with the Radical Republicans; but what he offered in policy, he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate but found support from Horace Greeley, who sought any chance to defeat Seward, with whom he now had a bitter feud.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the 1858 Lincoln–Douglas debates and had represented Illinois in the House of Representatives.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln had been quietly eyeing a run since the debates, ensuring that they were widely published and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He gained great renown with his acclaimed February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination, even though he had not yet announced his intention to run.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delivered in Seward's home state and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican Party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics, as Southerners and Democrats claimed.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] So it did at the Illinois state convention, a week before the national convention.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Young politician Richard Oglesby found several fence rails that Lincoln may have split as a youngster and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing his and his political allies' expectations.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's campaign managers had printed and distributed thousands of fake convention admission tickets to Lincoln supporters to ensure and increase the crowd's support.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He engineered that the convention would be held in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person and left the task of delegate wrangling to several close friends.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first round of voting predictably produced a lead for Seward, but not a majority, with Lincoln in second place.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The second round eliminated most of the minor contenders, with voters switching mostly to Seward or Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The convention remained deadlocked, however, and successful political maneuvering by Lincoln's delegates persuaded some delegates to abandon Seward in favor of Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, his position on economic issues, his western origins, and his strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the presidential nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Clay.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states, but opposed slavery in the territories.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The platform promised tariffs protecting industry and workers, a Homestead Act granting free farmland in the West to settlers, and the funding of a transcontinental railroad.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was no mention of Mormonism (which had been condemned in the Party's 1856 platform), the Fugitive Slave Act, personal liberty laws, or the Dred Scott decision.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While the Seward forces were disappointed at the nomination of a little-known western upstart, they rallied behind Lincoln, while abolitionists were angry at the selection of a moderate and had little faith in Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas from Illinois, James Guthrie from Kentucky, Robert Mercer Taliaferro Hunter from Virginia, Joseph Lane from Oregon, Daniel S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Dickinson from New York, and Andrew Johnson from Tennessee, while three other candidates, Isaac Toucey from Connecticut, James Pearce from Maryland, and Jefferson Davis from Mississippi (the future president of the Confederate States) also received votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, a moderate on the slavery issue who favored "popular sovereignty", was ahead on the first ballot, but was 56½ votes short of securing the nomination.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the 57th ballot, with Douglas still ahead, but 51½ votes short of the nomination, the exhausted and desperate delegates agreed on May 3 to cease voting and adjourn the convention.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While some considered Horatio Seymour a compromise candidate for the national Democratic nomination at the reconvening convention in Baltimore, Seymour wrote a letter to the editor of his local newspaper declaring unreservedly that he was not a candidate for either spot on the ticket.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After two ballots - the 59th ballot overall - the remaining Democrats nominated Stephen A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election would now pit Lincoln against his longtime political rival, whom Lincoln had lost to in the Illinois senate race just two years earlier.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That two candidates were from Illinois showed the importance of the West in the election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Benjamin Fitzpatrick from Alabama was nominated for vice president, he refused the nomination.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the convention concluded with no vice presidential nominee, Douglas offered the vice presidential nomination to Herschel V.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The southern delegates walked out of Institute Hall on April 30, moving at first to the Saint Andrews Hall, then to Military Hall on May 1st.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 3rd, when the northern delegates left Charleston, the southern delegates left as well, reconvening at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, Virginia on June 11.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the Democrats reconvened at Front Street Theater in Baltimore, they rejoined (except South Carolina and Florida, who had stayed in Richmond).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the convention seated two replacement delegations on June 18, they walked out again or boycotted the convention, accompanied by nearly all other Southern delegates and erstwhile Convention chair Caleb Cushing, a New Englander and former member of Franklin Pierce's cabinet.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This larger group met immediately in Baltimore's Maryland Institute Hall, with Cushing again presiding.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They adopted the pro-slavery platform rejected at Charleston, and nominated Vice President John C.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge for president, and Senator Joseph Lane from Oregon for vice president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Yancey and some (less than half) of the bolters - almost entirely from the Lower South - met on June 28 at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, along with the South Carolina and Florida delegations, at a convention that affirmed the nominations of Breckinridge and Lane.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Besides the Democratic parties in the Southern states, the Breckinridge/Lane ticket was also supported by the Buchanan administration.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan's own continued prestige in his home state of Pennsylvania ensured that Breckinridge would be the principal Democratic candidate in that populous state.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge was the last sitting vice president nominated for president until Richard Nixon in 1960.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Constitutional Union Party was formed by remnants of both the defunct Know Nothing and Whig parties who were unwilling to join either the Republicans or the Democrats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The new party's members hoped to stave off Southern secession by avoiding the slavery issue.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They met in the Eastside District Courthouse of Baltimore and nominated John Bell from Tennessee for president over Governor Sam Houston of Texas on the second ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett was nominated for vice president at the convention on May 9, 1860, one week before Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Bell was a former Whig who had opposed the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the Lecompton Constitution.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett had been president of Harvard University and Secretary of State in the Millard Fillmore administration.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Radical Abolitionist Party was a remnant of the Liberty Party that formed after most former Liberty and Free Soil Party members joined the Republicans in the 1850s.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A convention of one hundred delegates was held in Convention Hall, Syracuse, New York, on August 29, 1860.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delegates were in attendance from New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, Kentucky, and Massachusetts.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gerrit Smith, a prominent abolitionist and the 1848 presidential nominee of the original Liberty Party, had sent a letter in which he stated that his health had been so poor that he had not been able to be away from home since 1858.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, he remained popular in the party because he had helped inspire some of John Brown's supporters at the Raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his letter, Smith donated $50 to pay for the printing of ballots in the various states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was quite a spirited contest between the friends of Gerrit Smith and William Goodell in regard to the nomination for the presidency.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In spite of his professed ill health, Gerrit Smith was nominated for president and Samuel McFarland from Pennsylvania was nominated for vice president.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In Ohio, Illinois, and Indiana, slates of presidential electors pledged to Smith and McFarland ran with the name of the Union Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They received a total of 176 votes in the general election, 0.004% of the total.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The People's Party was a loose association of the supporters of Governor Samuel Houston.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 20, 1860, the party held what it termed a national convention to nominate Houston for president on the San Jacinto Battlefield in Texas.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston's supporters at the gathering did not nominate a vice presidential candidate, since they expected later gatherings to carry out that function.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later mass meetings were held in northern cities, such as New York City on May 30, 1860, but they too failed to nominate a vice presidential candidate.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston, never enthusiastic about running for the presidency, soon became convinced that he had no chance of winning and that his candidacy would only make it easier for the Republican candidate to win.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He withdrew from the race on August 16, and urged the formation of a Unified "Union" ticket in opposition to Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In their campaigning, Bell and Douglas both claimed that disunion would not necessarily follow a Lincoln election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, loyal army officers in Virginia, Kansas and South Carolina warned Lincoln of military preparations to the contrary.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mexican War hero Winfield Scott suggested to Lincoln that he assume the powers of a commander-in-chief before inauguration.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, historian Bruce Chadwick observes that Lincoln and his advisors ignored the widespread alarms and threats of secession as mere election trickery.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Indeed, voting in the South was not as monolithic as the Electoral College map would make it seem.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Economically, culturally, and politically, the South was made up of three regions.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the states of the Upper South, also known as the Border South (Delaware, Maryland, Kentucky, and Missouri), unionist popular votes were scattered among Lincoln, Douglas, and Bell, to form a majority in all four.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the four Middle South states, there was a unionist majority divided between Douglas and Bell in Virginia and Tennessee; in North Carolina and Arkansas, the unionist (Bell and Douglas) vote approached a majority.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In three of the seven Deep South states, unionists (Bell and Douglas) won divided majorities in Georgia and Louisiana and neared it in Alabama.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge convincingly carried only four of the seven states of the Deep South (South Carolina, Florida, Mississippi, and Texas).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Deep South states had the largest enslaved populations, and consequently the smallest enfranchised free white populations.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the slave states, the three states with the highest voter turnouts voted the most one-sided.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Texas, with five percent of the total wartime South's population, voted 75 percent Breckinridge.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kentucky and Missouri, with one-fourth of the total population, voted 73 percent pro-Union Bell, Douglas and Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In comparison, the other six states of the Deep South made up one-fourth of the Confederate voting population; this was split 57 percent for Breckinridge versus 43 percent for the two pro-union candidates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The four states that were admitted to the Confederacy after Fort Sumter held almost half its population, and voted a narrow combined majority of 53 percent for the pro-union candidates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the eleven states that would later declare their secession from the Union and be controlled by Confederate armies, ballots for Lincoln were cast only in Virginia, where he received 1,929 votes (1.15 percent of the total).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The vast majority of the votes Lincoln received were cast in border counties of what would soon become West Virginia – the future state accounted for 1,832 of Lincoln's 1,929 votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes at all in 121 of the state's at-the-time 145 counties (including 31 of the 50 that would form West Virginia), received a single vote in three counties and received ten or fewer votes in nine of the 24 counties where he polled votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hancock County (Virginia's northernmost at the time) returned Lincoln's best result – he polled over 40% of the vote there and finished in second place (Lincoln polled only eight votes fewer than Breckinridge).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 97 votes cast for Lincoln in the state's post-1863 boundaries, 93 were polled in four counties along the Potomac River and four were tallied in the coastal city of Portsmouth.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Lincoln received no votes in 10 Southern states, this was not because he was removed from the ballot in those states, but rather due to the Republican Party's absence in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One key difference between modern elections and those of the mid-nineteenth century is that at the time the state did not print and distribute ballots.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since voters did not choose the president directly, but rather presidential electors, the only way for a voter to meaningfully support a particular candidate for president was cast a ballot for citizens of his state who would have pledged to vote for the candidate in the Electoral College.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In ten southern slave states, no citizen would publicly pledge to vote for Abraham Lincoln, so citizens there had no legal means to vote for the Republican nominee.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In most of Virginia, no publisher would print ballots for Lincoln's pledged electors.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the four slave states that did not secede Lincoln came third in Delaware and fourth in Missouri, Kentucky and Maryland.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within the fifteen slave states, Lincoln won only two counties out of 996, Missouri's St.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 1856 election, the Republican candidate for president had received no votes at all in twelve of the fourteen slave states with a popular vote (these being the same states as in the 1860 election, plus Missouri and Virginia).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election was held on Tuesday, November 6, 1860, and was noteworthy for the exaggerated sectionalism and voter enthusiasm in a country that was soon to dissolve into civil war.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Voter turnout was 81.2%, the highest in American history up to that time, and the second-highest overall (exceeded only in the election of 1876).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] 31.5% of the voting age population voted.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Since Andrew Jackson had won re-election in 1832, all six subsequent presidents had only won one term, while the last four of those had won with a popular vote under 51 percent.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the Electoral College with less than 40 percent of the popular vote nationwide by carrying states above the Mason–Dixon line and north of the Ohio River, plus the states of California and Oregon in the Far West.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unlike every preceding president-elect, Lincoln did not carry even one slave state; he instead carried all eighteen free states exclusively.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes in ten Southern states because the Republican Party was absent in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were no ballots distributed for Lincoln in ten of the Southern states: Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This withheld 61 potential electoral votes from Lincoln, a fifth of what was the total 303 available to the other candidates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a similar divide between North and South electors, Breckenridge carried nine of the ten states that withheld Lincoln from the ballot, the exception being Tennessee.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It should be further noted that, prior to the introduction of the secret ballot in the 1880s, the concept of ballot access did not exist in the sense it does today: there was no standardized state-issued ballot for a candidate to "appear" on.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead, presidential ballots were printed and distributed by agents of the candidates and their parties, who organized slates of would-be electors publicly pledged to vote for a particular candidate.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the second-lowest share of the popular vote among all winning presidential candidates in U.S. history.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's share of the popular vote would likely have been even lower if there had been a popular vote in South Carolina, though conversely it would likely have been marginally higher had Republican ballots been widely available to voters throughout the Southern States.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican victory resulted from the concentration of votes in the free states, which together controlled a majority of the presidential electors.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Wide Awakes young Republican men's organization massively expanded registered voter lists, and population increases in the free states had far exceeded those seen in the slave states for many years before the election of 1860, hence free states dominated in the Electoral College.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gasconade County, Missouri has voted for a Republican presidential candidate in every election from 1860 on, which, as of 2024, makes it the longest Republican winning streak in presidential elections in the nation.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite Lincoln's commanding victory, this was the first election in American history in which the winner failed to win a majority of votes in his home county, with Lincoln narrowly losing Sangamon County, Illinois to Douglas, his main opponent in the North.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Regardless, Lincoln won absolute majorities (>50%) in enough states, that if he lost all states that he took with pluralities, he still would have received enough electoral votes to win.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In short, even if Ranked-Choice Voting, or any other runoff system had been in effect in every state, Lincoln still would have won on the first round.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey, where anti-Lincoln votes were combined into fusion tickets, Lincoln still won New York and Pennsylvania and split New Jersey.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, a shift of 25,000 votes to the fusion ticket in New York would have left Lincoln with 145 electoral votes — seven votes short of winning the Electoral College — and forced a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Alternatively, a shift of only 15,400 votes over California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Oregon, and Rhode Island would have left Lincoln short of the necessary 152 electoral votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the five states that Lincoln failed to carry, he received 20 percent of the vote in only one (Delaware) and 10 percent of the vote in one more (Missouri).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Like Lincoln, Breckinridge and Bell won no electoral votes outside of their respective sections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Bell retired to his family business, quietly supporting his state's secession, Breckinridge served as a Confederate general.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He finished second in the Electoral College with 72 votes, carrying eleven of fifteen slave states (including South Carolina, whose electors were chosen by the state legislature, not popular vote).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge stood a distant third in national popular vote at eighteen percent, but accrued 50 to 75 percent in the first seven states that would form the Confederate States of America.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He took nine of the eleven states that eventually joined, plus the border slave states of Delaware and Maryland, losing only Virginia and Tennessee.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge received very little support in the free states, showing some strength only in California, Oregon, Pennsylvania, and Connecticut.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell carried three slave states (Tennessee, Kentucky, and Virginia) and lost Maryland by only 722 votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, he finished a remarkable second in all slave states won by Breckinridge or Douglas.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He won 45 to 47 percent in Maryland, Tennessee, and North Carolina and canvassed respectably with 36 to 40 percent in Missouri, Arkansas, Louisiana, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell himself had hoped that he would take over the former support of the extinct Whig Party in free states, but the majority of this support went to Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thus, except for running mate Everett's home state of Massachusetts, and California, Bell received even less support in the free states than did Breckinridge, and consequently came in last in the national popular vote, at 12.62%.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas was the only candidate who won electoral votes in both slave and free states (free New Jersey and slave Missouri).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His support was the most widespread geographically; he finished second behind Lincoln in the popular vote with 29.52%, but last in the Electoral College.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His 12 electoral votes are the lowest for a Democrat in history.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas attained a 28 to 47% share in the states of the Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, and Trans-Mississippi West, but slipped to 19 to 39% in New England.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Outside his regional section, Douglas took 15 to 17% of the popular vote total in the slave states of Kentucky, Alabama, and Louisiana, then 10 percent or less in the nine remaining slave states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, in his "Norfolk Doctrine", reiterated in North Carolina, promised to keep the Union together by coercion if states proceeded to secede: the popular vote for Lincoln and Douglas combined was 69.17% of the turnout.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Republican ticket was the first successful national ticket that did not feature a Southerner, and the election marked the end of Southern political dominance in the United States.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between 1789 and 1860, Southerners had been president for two-thirds of the era, and had held the offices of Speaker of the House and President pro tempore of the Senate during much of that time.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since 1791, Southerners had constituted a majority of the Supreme Court.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (b) *The option of Lincoln was absent from 20.13% of ballots across ten states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln's victory and imminent inauguration as president was the immediate cause for declarations of secession by seven Southern states (South Carolina, Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas) from 20 December 1860 to 1 February 1861.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They then formed the Confederate States of America.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On 9 February 1861, Jefferson Davis was elected president of the Confederacy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All of the secessionist activity was motivated by fear for the institution of slavery in the South.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If the President (and, by extension, the appointed federal officials in the South, such as district attorneys, marshals, postmasters, and judges) opposed slavery, it might collapse.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were fears that abolitionist agents would infiltrate the South and foment slave insurrections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (The noted secessionist William Lowndes Yancey, speaking at New York's Cooper Institute in October 1860, asserted that with abolitionists in power, "Emissaries will percolate between master [and] slave as water between the crevices of rocks underground.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They will be found everywhere, with strychnine to put in our wells.") Less radical Southerners thought that with Northern antislavery dominance of the federal government, slavery would eventually be abolished, regardless of present constitutional limits.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bertram Wyatt-Brown argues that secessionists desired independence as necessary for their honor.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They could no longer tolerate Northern state attitudes that regarded slave ownership as a great sin and Northern politicians who insisted on stopping the spread of slavery.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another bloc of Southerners resented Northern criticism of slavery and restrictions on slavery but opposed secession as dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, the "conditional Unionists" also hoped that when faced with secession, Northerners would stifle anti-slavery rhetoric and accept pro-slavery rules for the territories.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was that group that prevented immediate secession in Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas when Lincoln took office on March 4, 1861.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He took no action against the secessionists in the seven "Confederate" states, but also declared that secession had no legal validity and refused to surrender federal property in those states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (He also reiterated his opposition to slavery anywhere in the territories.) Preparing to form an army, on 6 March 1861 Davis called for 100,000 volunteers to serve for twelve months.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The political standoff continued until mid-April, when Davis ordered Confederate troops to bombard and capture Fort Sumter.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln then called for troops to put down rebellion, which wiped out the possibility that the crisis could be resolved by compromise.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nearly all "conditional Unionists" joined the secessionists, including for example presidential candidate John Bell of the Constitutional Union Party, whose home state of Tennessee was the last to secede.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Virginia convention and the reconvened Arkansas convention both declared secession, as did the legislatures of Tennessee and North Carolina; all four states joined the Confederacy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Missouri and Kentucky stayed in the United States, but had unrecognized dual governments.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the Civil War begun, Douglas then threw his support behind Lincoln and undertook a tour to bolster support for the Union, making visits to Virginia, Ohio and Illinois.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Douglas declared "There are no neutrals, only patriots and traitors".
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, three months after Lincoln's inauguration, Douglas contracted typhoid fever and died in Chicago on June 3, 1861.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The **1862–63 United States House of Representatives elections** were held between June 2, 1862, and November 3, 1863, to elect the 184 members and eight non-voting delegates of the House of Representatives.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition lost seats but retained an overall majority against the backdrop of the American Civil War.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In the first real test of opposition to the Lincoln administration, the Democratic Party made large gains in these and concurrent elections held in 1862 and 1863 but failed to take control of the House.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Much of the campaign focussed on emancipation and Lincoln's handling of the war.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, weeks before critical races in Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania, (October 14) and New York (November 3).
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats denounced emancipation as tyrannical and a threat to white supremacy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democratic election propaganda charged their opponents with bloodlust and religious fanaticism and made frequent appeals to anti-Black racism.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] While Radical Republicans defended the measure, others felt compelled to distance themselves from the president's policy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In Indiana and Ohio, the Union Party downplayed the slavery issue.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The issue was particularly troublesome for Unionists in the border states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kentucky's Union Democratic Party disavowed the proclamation ahead of congressional elections held in August 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In Maryland and Missouri, Unionists welcomed emancipation in principle but divided over questions over gradual versus immediate abolition and the enlistment of Black soldiers.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Other issues impacted the election, including Lincoln's suspension of *habeas corpus*, conscription, and the progress of the war.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Inconclusive Union victories at Antietam, Corinth, and Perryville contributed to a perception that the administration's military strategy was ineffective.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats charged the administration with subordinating the restoration of the Union to the radical social policy of the abolitionist movement.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] During this election, the Republican Party formed a coalition with War Democrats and border state unionists who supported the war effort.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In most states, this coalition was known as the Union Party or as the Republican–Union Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In parts of New England and the Upper Midwest, pro-administration candidates still called themselves Republicans.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Missouri Unionists were known as the Emancipation Party and split between Immediate and Gradual Emancipationists during this election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition became the basis for the National Union Party which contested the next election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] While contemporary observers interpreted the elections as a "severe reproof" of the administration, the results of the elections were inconclusive.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats flipped more than 30 seats compared to the last election, while Republican–Unionists suffered serious losses across the Lower North.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The strong showing for Union candidates in the border states, however, salvaged the Republican–Unionist majority.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Among the defeated Republican–Unionists was the incumbent speaker of the House of Representatives Galusha A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Grow, who lost his Pennsylvania district to a Democratic challenger.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] This was the last election in which a sitting speaker of the House was defeated for re-election until 1994, when George Nethercutt defeated Tom Foley in Washington's 5th congressional district.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Reapportionment took place following the 1860 United States census.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The 1862 apportionment act increased the size of the House to 241 seats from 233.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Fifty-eight seats were vacant due to secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Three seats were transferred from Virginia to West Virginia following the latter's admission on June 20, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] One seat was allocated to Nevada upon its admission on October 31, 1864, increasing the size of the House to 242 seats and the number of elected members to 184.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Special elections were held in 1862 and 1863 to fill 12 vacancies in the 37th Congress and four vacancies in the 38th Congress.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Alabama did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Arkansas held no elections in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Late elections were held in 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] California elected its members on September 2, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Voters chose three members on a statewide general ticket to represent the state's at-large congressional district.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 6, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Delaware elected its member on November 1, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Florida did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Illinois elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Indiana elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Iowa elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kansas elected its member on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Whereas the Union Party replaced the Republicans in most states during the war, the Kansas Republican Party remained active.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In a factional schism, opponents of U.S. senator Jim Lane split from the Republican Party in 1862 to form the Union Party with the support of the state's Democrats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Parrott for Congress, was not affiliated with the national Republican–Union coalition and broke apart during the 1864 presidential election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kentucky elected its members on August 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louisiana held no elections for the 38th Congress in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Late elections were held on September 5, 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Maine elected its members on September 8, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Maryland elected its members on November 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Massachusetts elected its members on November 1, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Massachusetts Republicans resisted incorporation into the Union Party in 1861 and 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Conservative Republicans, former Whigs, and Democrats attended the state convention of the Constitutional Union Party which nominated candidates for the upcoming elections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The convention called itself the People's Party in order to attract votes from Democrats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Conservative former Whigs and Republicans in the party expressed strong support for the Lincoln administration during the spring and summer under the belief that the president firmly opposed emancipation.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, issued less than two weeks before the state convention met, helped to divide and defeat the new party in its infancy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Michigan elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] A Democratic proposal for a bipartisan Union ticket was rejected by the Radical leadership of the Michigan Republican Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Democrats went ahead with plans for a Union state convention and called themselves Union Democrats or Fusionists during the campaign in hopes of attracting votes from disaffected Conservative Republicans.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Some conservatives did support the Union ticket, which was disavowed by the Republican state committee.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Minnesota elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Mississippi did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Missouri elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Missouri Unionists contested this election as the Emancipation Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The party was divided ideologically between conservative Claybanks, who favored a plan of gradual emancipation, and radical Charcoals, who supported immediate emancipation.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louis, Gradual and Immediate Emancipationists ran opposing tickets.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Some sources list the Gradual Emancipation candidates as Republicans; however, the Republican state committee deliberately deemphasized old party labels in its call for the state convention which gave rise to the Emancipation Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Francis Preston Blair Jr., the most prominent leader of the Antebellum Missouri Republican Party, was nominated on the Union Emancipation ticket in Missouri's 1st congressional district and contested the election as a Gradual Emancipationist.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Hampshire elected its members on March 10, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Jersey elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] New York elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] North Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Ohio elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Oregon elected its members on June 2, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Rhode Island elected its members on April 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] South Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Tennessee did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Texas did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Vermont elected its members on September 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The Restored Government of Virginia held elections in three districts on May 28, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] West Virginia elected its members on October 22, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The state and its congressional districts had formed part of Western Virginia before being admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, with the consent of the Restored Government of Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The West Virginian members were seated on December 7, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Wisconsin elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The **1862–63 United States Senate elections** were held from January 4, 1862, to November 13, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Regularly scheduled elections were held for 20 out of the 70 seats in the United States Senate, and special elections were held in Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Missouri, New Jersey, Oregon, and Rhode Island.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Republican–Union coalition retained their majority despite an unfavorable national environment.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] U.S. senators are divided into three classes whose six-year terms are staggered, such that one-third of the Senate is elected every two years.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Senators in Class 1 were elected in 1862 and 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Prior to ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment, senators were elected by the U.S. state legislatures.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] There was no fixed calendar, and states held elections on various dates preceding the first session of Congress.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In states with split partisan control of the legislature, multiple rounds of voting could be required to elect a senator, leading to extended vacancies.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] While Democrats made significant gains in the 1862–63 United States House of Representatives elections and won important state races in Illinois, Indiana, and New York, the party failed to improve its standing in the Senate and instead suffered a net loss of seats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Republican–Unionists flipped Democratic-held seats in California, Oregon, and Minnesota, while Democrats flipped Republican-held seats in Illinois and Pennsylvania.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In Indiana and New Jersey, Democrats defeated Republican–Union incumbents appointed to fill vacancies caused by the expulsion or death of a Democratic senator.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Radical Unionists gained both Missouri seats held by Democrats prior to 1862, and Constitutional Unionists flipped a Republican-held seat in Rhode Island.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] No election was held in Tennessee following the resignation of Democrat Andrew Johnson, increasing the number of vacancies to 20.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Pearce of Maryland reduced the Democratic caucus to nine seats before the start of the 38th Congress.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Missouri Radical Unionists, both Union senators from West Virginia, and Constitutional Unionist William Sprague IV of Rhode Island subsequently caucused with the Republican–Union majority, increasing their caucus to 36 seats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The elections took place against the backdrop of the American Civil War and the end of slavery in the United States in what was the first real test of Democratic opposition to the Lincoln administration.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The war disrupted established party systems in the free states and the loyal border states, resulting in a partial political realignment.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In the Lower North, Republicans and War Democrats contested these elections as the Union Party, while Republicans maintained a separate organization in New England and the Upper Midwest.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In Massachusetts and Rhode Island, anti-abolitionist conservatives formed new political parties composed of most Democrats and Constitutional Unionists.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In the border states, Unionists were ascendant but internally divided over issues relating to slavery and Reconstruction, resulting in protracted legislative battles in Missouri and West Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Emancipation and the status of freedpeople were major issues during the campaign and a significant factor in party alignments.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Lincoln's initial plan of gradual, compensated emancipation paired with the colonization of freedpeople outside the United States was jointly rejected by abolitionists who favored immediate, unqualified emancipation, and by Democrats and conservatives who opposed emancipation altogether.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Radical Republican opposition to any compromise with slavery was the catalyst for the formation of the People's Party in Massachusetts, who campaigned in support of Lincoln's proposal.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The manner and timing of emancipation split the Missouri unionist movement, leading Immediate Emancipationists to organize the Radical Union Party in September 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The appearance of the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation in September 1862 interrupted the campaign and undercut the momentum of pro-Lincoln conservatives.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Democrats attempted to capitalize on racist backlash to the proclamation, warning that emancipation would precipitate slave rebellions and large-scale Black migration to the free states, and charging the administration of prolonging the war in service of religious fanaticism.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] While Radical Republicans celebrated the proclamation, Moderates and Conservatives feared the president's policy spelled electoral defeat.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In Ohio, Republican–Unionists avoided mention of slavery in their state platform, and the Indiana Union Party called for the restoration of the Union with the rights of the states fully intact.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Each block represents one of the 68 seats in the U.S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] They are arranged so that the parties are separated, and a majority is clear by crossing the middle.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Hicks was appointed to fill the vacancy created by the death of James A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Pearce of Maryland, flipping the seat from Democratic to Union.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Five senators elected as border state Unionists (Peter G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Willey of West Virginia), Radical Unionists (B.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson of Missouri), or Constitutional Unionists (William Sprague of Rhode Island) caucused with the Republican–Union majority after the start of the 38th Congress, increasing their caucus to 36 seats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Special elections were held to fill six vacancies in the 37th United States Congress.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Eighteen senators were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were elected in 1863 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Democrat Milton Latham was elected in 1860 to fill the vacancy created by the death of David C.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Union members of the legislature held a caucus from January 13 to February 9, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Phelps led on the first ballot, but without a majority.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] During the balloting, an internal inquiry found that Phelps's supporters had offered bribes to several members in exchange for their votes.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Although Phelps denied the allegations, the stigma of corruption in effect ended his candidacy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Conness was nominated on the final ballot with 60 votes to 29 for Sargent, three for Phelps, and eight for other candidates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The California State Legislature met in joint session on February 10, 1863, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Conness defeated the Democratic candidate Benjamin Shurtleff on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Republican James Dixon was elected in 1856.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Union members of the legislature held a caucus on May 15, 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Dixon defeated the other candidates on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate and the House of Representatives met separately on May 22, 1862, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Dixon defeated the Democratic candidate Charles Chapman on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] A coalition of Republicans and War Democrats organized the Union Party in Delaware ahead of the 1862 state elections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Unionist William Cannon won the 1862 Delaware gubernatorial election, but Democrats retained narrow majorities in both chambers of the legislature.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Delaware General Assembly met in joint session on January 8, 1863, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Bayard defeated the Union candidate Edward G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Two-term Democrat Stephen Mallory withdrew from the Senate on March 14, 1861, following the secession of Florida.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Florida Legislature did not hold an election for the next term, and the seat remained vacant until 1868.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Browning was appointed in 1861 to fill the vacancy created by the death of Stephen A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Union Party was initially confident in its ability to retain control of the Illinois General Assembly, a feat which would allow it to elect a successor to complete Douglas's unexpired term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The campaign was interrupted by the appearance of the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation in September 1862, which placed the national Lincoln administration on ground long occupied by Radical Republicans.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The proclamation inflamed factional conflict between Radicals and Moderates in the Union Party and emboldened the Democratic opposition, who accused the administration of seeking to "Africanize" Illinois.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Illinois Democrats were victorious in state elections held in the fall of 1862, electing nine of the state's fourteen U.S. representatives and a 27-seat majority in the legislature.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The General Assembly met on January 12, 1863, to hold a special election for the unexpired term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Richardson defeated the Union candidate Richard Yates on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Wright was appointed in 1862 to fill the vacancy created by the expulsion of Jesse D.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] With Bright's expulsion coming little more than a year before the end of his term on March 4, 1863, the Indiana General Assembly would hold concurrent elections in January 1863: a special election for the remainder of the unexpired term, and the regularly scheduled election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Wright and Bright had waged a bitter struggle for control of the Indiana Democratic Party during the preceding decade; by appointing Wright to Bright's former seat in the Senate, Indiana governor Oliver P.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Morton helped to bring Wright's War Democratic supporters into Indiana's nascent Union Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] From the outset of the campaign, Democrats accused the national administration of using the war as a pretext for emancipation.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] These fears were seemingly vindicated by the appearance of the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation in September 1862.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Democrats launched an unprecedented racist campaign against the proclamation that confounded the attempts of moderate Unionists to defend emancipation as a military necessity.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In the fall legislative elections, Democrats won majorities in both chambers of the General Assembly, paving the way for the election of a Democratic senator in January.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Democratic members of the legislature held a caucus on January 9, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] David Turpie was nominated for the unexpired term and Thomas A.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Hendricks was nominated for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The General Assembly met in joint session on January 14, 1863, to hold concurrent elections for both terms.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Turpie and Hendricks were respectively elected.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Wright was not a candidate in the special election.
