[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Democrat Jefferson Davis withdrew from the Senate on March 14, 1861, following the secession of Mississippi.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Mississippi Legislature did not hold an election for the next term, and the seat remained vacant until 1870.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Three elections were held in Missouri, due to the expulsions of Trusten Polk and Waldo P.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] With Polk's expulsion coming little more than a year before the end of his term on March 4, 1863, the Missouri General Assembly would hold special elections for both seats, followed by the regularly-scheduled election for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Missouri Unionists were divided in their responses to emancipation and the related issue of Reconstruction.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Three main ideological camps emerged: radical Charcoals, who supported immediate emancipation; conservative Claybanks, who favored Lincoln's initial plan of gradual emancipation; and ultra-conservative Snowflakes, who opposed emancipation altogether.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Louis, the ideological divide resulted in a formal split between the Immediatist and Gradualist wings of the Emancipation Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Elections held in the fall of 1862 resulted in a clear majority for the Emancipationists in the General Assembly, while five Conservatives and four Radicals were elected to the U.S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Emancipation members of the legislature held a caucus on January 3, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Conservatives boycotted the proceedings.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson was nominated for the Class 1 seat and B.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Gratz Brown was nominated for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The General Assembly met in joint session on January 6, 1863, to hold concurrent special elections for both seats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson was elected to the Class 1 seat for the term ending March 4.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The special election for the Class 3 seat remained deadlocked after multiple rounds of voting, and the joint session adjourned without making a choice.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The joint session reconvened in November 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In the interim, the Radicals held a convention at Jefferson City that organized the Radical Union Party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The meeting nominated Brown for the Class 3 seat and Benjamin F.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Conservatives were united in support of the administration of Hamilton R.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Gamble, but lacked a formal party organization.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Closely-fought judicial elections in the fall of 1863 helped to clarify party lines.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson had campaigned for the Conservative judicial candidates, but was aligned with the Radicals on emancipation and faced a Conservative opponent in his bid for re-election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] In the legislature, the Radical Unionists had 65 votes on the joint ballot, just short of an overall majority, while Henderson's allies held the balance of power.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Radical Union members held a caucus after the first round of voting on November 12 and agreed to form a coalition with Henderson's supporters.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Brown was subsequently elected to the Class 3 seat and Henderson was re-elected to the Class 1 seat as a Radical Unionist.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson was appointed in 1862 to fill the vacancy created by the expulsion of Trusten Polk.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The General Assembly met on January 6, 1863, to hold a special election for the unexpired term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Henderson defeated the Conservative candidate Robert Wilson on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Conservative Robert Wilson was appointed in 1862 to fill the vacancy created by the expulsion of Waldo P.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] He was not a candidate for re-election to the Class 3 seat.
