[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The caucus selected Cameron on the basis of these assurances in the final hours before the election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Pennsylvania General Assembly met in joint session on January 13, 1863, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Buckalew defeated Cameron on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] There were two elections in Rhode Island, due to the resignation of James F.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Simmons was re-elected non-consecutively in 1857.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Rhode Island General Assembly met in joint session on May 28, 1862, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Democratic and Constitutional Union candidate William Sprague defeated Simmons and Nathan F.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Sprague subsequently caucused with the Republican–Union majority in the Senate and served the remainder of his term as a Republican.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Simmons resigned from the Senate on August 15, 1862, less than a year before the end of his term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The General Assembly met in joint session on September 5, 1862, to hold a special election for the unexpired term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Democratic and Constitutional Union candidate Samuel G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Democrat Andrew Johnson resigned on March 4, 1862, following his appointment as the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Tennessee General Assembly did not hold an election for the next term, and the seat remained vacant until 1866.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Wigfall was expelled from the Senate on July 11, 1861.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Texas Legislature did not hold an election for the next term, and the seat remained vacant until 1870.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Two-term Republican Solomon Foot was re-elected in 1856.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate and the House of Representatives met separately on October 14, 1862, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Foot defeated Daniel Kellogg on the first ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Willey was elected in 1861 to fill the vacancy created by the expulsion of James M.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Restored Virginia General Assembly met on January 23, 1863, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Voting proceeded separately in the Senate and the House of Delegates, after which the votes were tallied jointly.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Bowden defeated Willey on the second ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] West Virginia elected two senators following its admission on June 20, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The West Virginia Legislature met on August 4, 1863, to hold elections for both seats.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Members voted for two candidates on the first ballot; voting proceeded separately in the Senate and the House of Delegates, after which the votes were tallied jointly.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Willey was elected on the first ballot; Archibald W.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Cambpell finished second, but without a majority.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] On subsequent ballots, each member cast one vote.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Van Winkle defeated Campbell on the sixth ballot.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Doolittle was a prominent supporter of colonizing free people of color outside the United States, considering such essential to any plan of emancipation.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] His endorsement of Lincoln's gradual emancipation scheme proved divisive with Wisconsin Republicans during the 1862 state elections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Radical Republicans mocked Doolittle's "wild notions of colonization" and called on Lincoln to adopt immediate emancipation and Black enlistment as the basis of a national policy.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The preliminary Emancipation Proclamation accepted the premise of the Radical position, helping to heal Republican divisions and sow discord among the opposition in the final weeks before the election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] The Wisconsin State Assembly met in joint session on January 22, 1863, to hold an election for the next term.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-63-united-states-senate-elections] Doolittle defeated the Democratic candidate Edward G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Elections were held in the United States on or before November 4, 1862, during the presidency of Abraham Lincoln.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] The Democratic Party flipped more than two dozen seats in the United States House of Representatives and won key state races in the Northern United States, but failed to end unified Republican-Union control of the White House and Congress.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Elections for the 38th United States Congress were staggered throughout 1862 and 1863, preceding the start of the first session.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Four of the 24 United States senators in Class I and 151 of the 180 United States representatives were elected in 1862, with the remainder chosen the following year.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Fifteen state gubernatorial elections, including two in the Confederacy, were also contested, alongside numerous state and local elections.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] The elections took place against the backdrop of the American Civil War and the end of slavery in the United States.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] In what was the first real test of Democratic opposition to the Lincoln administration, Democrats made a net gain of 29 seats in the House, won governorships in New Jersey and New York, and flipped partisan control of state legislatures in four Lower North states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Republican-Unionists flipped a Democratic-held United States Senate seat in Oregon, while the Constitutional Union Party flipped a Republican-held seat in Rhode Island.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Emancipation and the status of freedpeople were major issues during the campaign.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] The appearance of the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation in late September interrupted the elections, with significant implications for party alignments.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] In the Upper North, the proclamation undercut Conservative efforts to marginalize Radical Republicans within the Republican-Union coalition.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Democrats benefited from racist backlash to the proclamation in the Lower North, wielding anti-abolitionist rhetoric to great effect.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Opposition to conscription, Lincoln's suspension of *habeas corpus*, and a sagging war effort also contributed to the strong Democratic showing in the region.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] Despite the magnitude of the Democratic gains in 1862, Republican-Unionists were able to salvage their congressional majorities due to the support of Unionists from the border states.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1862-united-states-elections] The lack of absentee voting for soldiers contributed to the decline in the Republican-Union vote compared to 1860.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-alabama-gubernatorial-election] The **1863 Alabama gubernatorial election** took place on August 3, 1863 during the American Civil War in order to elect the governor of Alabama.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-alabama-gubernatorial-election] Whig Thomas Hill Watts won his first term as governor.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-alabama-gubernatorial-election] Watts and Shorter had faced each other before in the prior 1861 election, and the fervent secessionist Shorter won easily while enthusiasm for the American Civil War was still high.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-alabama-gubernatorial-election] However, as the war progressed, the economic and military situation deteriorated rapidly, with local anti-Confederate rebellions breaking out across the state, and many civilians facing destitution.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-alabama-gubernatorial-election] Under these conditions, Shorter was defeated in his bid for reelection.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The **1863 West Virginia gubernatorial election** was the first gubernatorial election, held on Thursday, May 28, 1863.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Boreman was elected virtually without opposition.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This was the first of two gubernatorial elections held in West Virginia during the American Civil War; 17 counties were occupied by Confederate military forces on Election Day and did not participate in the balloting.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] In a contested convention held at Parkersburg, West Virginia, the Union Party nominated Judge Arthur I.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Boreman over his nearest rival, Peter G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Despite fissures within the statehood movement driven by the Willey Amendment, an abolitionist proposal backed by U.S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Willey, no challenge to the Union ticket emerged from either the radical or conservative ends of the party.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Secessionists loyal to the Confederacy did not recognize the legitimacy of the new state and consequently did not participate in the campaign.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Boreman received over 99 percent of the vote in 33 participating counties against only three votes for other candidates.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Voter turnout was anemic, and newspapers complained of the slowness of the returns; however, by June 13, sufficient returns had been received for officials to certify Boreman's election.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] He was inaugurated as the first governor of West Virginia on June 20, 1863, in a ceremony at the Linsly Institute in Wheeling alongside other officers of the new state government.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cultural, economic, and regional differences had long separated Western Virginia from the eastern Tidewater counties that dominated political and economic life in Antebellum Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Slavery dominated the Tidewater, while it had a substantially weaker presence in the western counties, which remained economically underdeveloped.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] After 1830, the political orientation of the Shenandoah Valley shifted eastward as the region became more closely linked to slavery, while Northwestern Virginia grew increasingly alienated from the Tidewater.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Following the election of Abraham Lincoln and the commencement of hostilities between the United States and the Confederacy, the Virginia Secession Convention voted to secede from the Union on April 17, 1861; 26 of the 31 northwestern delegates voted against the ordinance.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Pierpont as head of the Restored Government of Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The success of the Western Virginia campaign established Union military control over the region and enabled unionist leaders to adopt and ratify a dismemberment ordinance between August 20 and October 24, beginning the process of formally separating from Virginia.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Although broadly popular in the Trans-Allegheny counties that had voted against secession, the new state movement divided unionist leaders.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Conservatives in the Union Party privately opposed dismemberment and attempted to undermine the statehood movement by annexing a number of secessionist southwestern counties to the proposed State of Kanawha.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Unionists were further divided by the requirement, introduced by Congress, that West Virginia abolish slavery as a condition for statehood.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Despite the opposition of such prominent unionists as John S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Carlile, the Willey Amendment (so named for its author, U.S.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Willey of Morgantown, West Virginia) was ratified by voters in March 1863, and West Virginia duly entered the Union on June 20.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Nevertheless, the battle over the Willey Amendment permanently divided West Virginian Unionists.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] From May 6 to 7, 1863, the Union Party's state convention was held to nominate candidates for multiple political offices.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Each county delegation was awarded a number of votes equal to its total white population.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] For the party's gubernatorial nomination Samuel Crane was nominated by James G.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On the first ballot Van Winkle received a plurality of the vote, but did not receive the nomination due to a majority being required.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] West withdrew Crane's nomination before the second ballot in which Boreman defeated Van Winkle.
[src:1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1863-west-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 28, 1863, Boreman won the gubernatorial election without opposition.
